===Etymology===
From Old French (French [[alambic]]), from mediæval Latin [[alembicus]], from Arabic {{ARchar|[[أنبيق|أنْبِيق]]}} ‘still’, from Greek [[αμβιξ]] ‘cup’, ‘cap of a still’.

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /ə'lɛmbɪk/

===Noun===
'''alembic'''
#an early [[chemical]] [[apparatus]], consisting of two [[retort]]s [[connected]] by a [[tube]], used to [[purify]] [[substance]]s by [[distillation]]
#:*'''1973''': We of all magical precipitates out of Europe’s groaning, clouded '''alembic''', we are the thinnest, the most dangerous, the handiest to secular uses — Thomas Pynchon, ''Gravity's Rainbow''

